import {Fragment as _Fragment, jsx as _jsx, jsxs as _jsxs} from "react/jsx-runtime";
export let _markdown = "\n\n# HiChIP Mode CLI\n\nHiChIP (Hi-C + ChIP) mode analyzes protein-centric chromatin interactions using restriction enzyme-based proximity ligation with immunoprecipitation enrichment.\n\n## Overview\n\n**Important**: HiChIP does **NOT** use linker sequences. Unlike ChIA-PET, HiChIP uses biotinylated nucleotides incorporated during fill-in after restriction digestion. The Chr3D pipeline:\n\n1. **Genomic Mapping** - Maps reads directly to reference genome (no linker filtering)\n2. **PET Purifying** - Removes same-fragment PETs using restriction site information\n3. **PET Categorization** - Classifies into iPET, sPET, oPET based on distance\n4. **Peak Calling** - Calls peaks from sPET using MACS3\n5. **Loop Calling** - Identifies significant loops with distance-corrected statistics\n\n## Command\n\n```bash\nchr3d run --mode hichip [options]\n```\n\n## Required Arguments\n\n| Argument              | Description                                      |\n| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |\n| `--fastq-r1`          | Input R1 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)          |\n| `--fastq-r2`          | Input R2 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)          |\n| `--genome-index`      | BWA-indexed reference genome FASTA               |\n| `--restriction-sites` | Restriction sites BED file (required for HiChIP) |\n| `--output-dir`        | Output directory                                 |\n\n## Optional Arguments\n\n| Argument                 | Default  | Description                                   |\n| ------------------------ | -------- | --------------------------------------------- |\n| `--threads`              | 24       | Number of threads                             |\n| `--use-bwa-mem`          | False    | Use BWA-MEM instead of BWA-ALN                |\n| `--genome-size`          | `hs`     | Genome size for MACS3 (`hs`, `mm`, or number) |\n| `--mapping-quality`      | 30       | Minimum mapping quality                       |\n| `--self-ligation-cutoff` | 8000     | Self-ligation distance cutoff (bp)            |\n| `--extension-length`     | 500      | Tag extension length for clustering (bp)      |\n| `--ipet-threshold`       | 2        | Minimum iPET count for loops                  |\n| `--fdr-cutoff`           | 0.05     | FDR cutoff for significant loops              |\n| `--sample-id`            | `sample` | Sample identifier                             |\n| `--keep-intermediates`   | False    | Keep intermediate files                       |\n| `--keep-sam`             | False    | Keep SAM files                                |\n| `--no-dedup`             | False    | Skip PCR duplicate removal                    |\n\n## Generating Restriction Sites\n\nBefore running HiChIP analysis, generate the restriction sites file:\n\n```bash\nchr3d generate-sites \\\n    --genome /path/to/hg38.fa \\\n    --enzyme MboI \\\n    --output /path/to/hg38_MboI_sites.bed\n```\n\n**Common Restriction Enzymes:**\n\n| Enzyme  | Recognition Site | Used In               |\n| ------- | ---------------- | --------------------- |\n| MboI    | GATC             | Most HiChIP protocols |\n| DpnII   | GATC             | Alternative to MboI   |\n| HindIII | AAGCTT           | Some Hi-C protocols   |\n| NcoI    | CCATGG           | Specific applications |\n\n## Complete Example\n\n```bash\n# Step 1: Generate restriction sites (one-time)\nchr3d generate-sites \\\n    --genome /ref/hg38.fa \\\n    --enzyme MboI \\\n    --output /ref/hg38_MboI_sites.bed\n\n# Step 2: Run HiChIP pipeline\nchr3d run --mode hichip \\\n    --fastq-r1 /data/H3K27ac_HiChIP_R1.fastq.gz \\\n    --fastq-r2 /data/H3K27ac_HiChIP_R2.fastq.gz \\\n    --genome-index /ref/hg38.fa \\\n    --restriction-sites /ref/hg38_MboI_sites.bed \\\n    --output-dir /output/hichip_analysis \\\n    --threads 16 \\\n    --use-bwa-mem \\\n    --genome-size hs \\\n    --mapping-quality 30 \\\n    --extension-length 500 \\\n    --ipet-threshold 2 \\\n    --fdr-cutoff 0.05 \\\n    --sample-id H3K27ac_HiChIP\n```\n\n## Pipeline Steps\n\n### Step 1: Skipped (No Linker Filtering)\n\nHiChIP does not use linkers, so this step is automatically skipped.\n\n```\nLog output: \"STEP 1: SKIPPED (HiChIP does not use linkers)\"\n```\n\n### Step 2: Genomic Mapping\n\nMaps paired-end reads directly to reference genome using BWA.\n\n```\nInput:  sample_R1.fastq.gz, sample_R2.fastq.gz\nOutput: step2_mapping/mapped.dedup.bedpe\n```\n\n**Mapping Statistics:**\n\n* Total read pairs processed\n* Successfully mapped pairs\n* Unique PETs after deduplication\n* Intra-chromosomal (cis) ratio\n* Inter-chromosomal (trans) ratio\n\n### Step 3: PET Purifying (Restriction Fragment Filtering)\n\nRemoves same-fragment PETs (invalid ligation products) using restriction site information.\n\n```\nInput:  step2_mapping/mapped.dedup.bedpe\n        restriction_sites.bed\nOutput: step3_purifying/purified.valid.bedpe\n        step3_purifying/purified.sameres.bedpe (removed)\n```\n\n**Why This Matters:**\n\n* Same-fragment PETs are artifacts from self-ligation\n* Valid PETs span different restriction fragments\n* This step is critical for HiChIP data quality\n\n### Step 4: PET Categorization\n\nClassifies PETs based on genomic distance.\n\n```\nInput:  step3_purifying/purified.valid.bedpe\nOutput: step4_categorization/categorized.ipet  (inter-ligation PETs)\n        step4_categorization/categorized.spet  (self-ligation PETs)\n        step4_categorization/categorized.opet  (other PETs)\n```\n\n**PET Categories:**\n\n* **iPET**: Long-range interactions (distance > 1kb for HiChIP)\n* **sPET**: Short-range/self-ligation (distance ≤ 1kb)\n* **oPET**: Wrong orientation or other issues\n\n### Step 5: Peak Calling\n\nCalls enrichment peaks from self-ligation PETs using MACS3.\n\n```\nInput:  step4_categorization/categorized.spet\nOutput: step5_peaks/peaks_peaks.narrowPeak\n        step5_peaks/peaks_summits.bed\n        step5_peaks/peaks_peaks.xls\n```\n\n**Note**: Peaks represent protein binding sites (e.g., H3K27ac marks).\n\n### Step 6: Loop Calling with Statistical Significance\n\nIdentifies significant chromatin loops using distance-corrected statistics.\n\n```\nInput:  step4_categorization/categorized.ipet\nOutput: step6_loops/loops.cluster.filtered\n        step6_loops/loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt\n```\n\n**Sub-steps:**\n\n1. **Pre-clustering (6.1)**\n   * Extends each tag by `extension-length` bp\n   * Groups overlapping extended tags into clusters\n\n2. **Anchor Clustering (6.2)**\n   * Merges pre-clusters into anchor pairs\n   * Creates interaction matrix between anchors\n\n3. **Statistical Significance (6.3)**\n   * Distance-corrected Poisson test (HiChIP-specific)\n   * Benjamini-Hochberg FDR correction\n   * Filters by `fdr-cutoff` threshold\n\n## Output Files\n\n```\noutput_dir/\n├── step1_linker_filtering/     (empty - HiChIP skips this)\n├── step2_mapping/\n│   ├── mapped.dedup.bedpe\n│   └── mapping_stats.txt\n├── step3_purifying/\n│   ├── purified.valid.bedpe\n│   └── purified.sameres.bedpe\n├── step4_categorization/\n│   ├── categorized.ipet\n│   ├── categorized.spet\n│   └── categorized.opet\n├── step5_peaks/\n│   ├── peaks_peaks.narrowPeak\n│   ├── peaks_summits.bed\n│   └── peaks_peaks.xls\n└── step6_loops/\n    ├── loops.cluster.filtered      (all loops meeting iPET threshold)\n    └── loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt (significant loops)\n```\n\n## Output Format\n\n### Loop File Format\n\nThe final loop file (`loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt`) contains:\n\n| Column      | Description                         |\n| ----------- | ----------------------------------- |\n| chr1        | Chromosome of anchor 1              |\n| start1      | Start position of anchor 1          |\n| end1        | End position of anchor 1            |\n| chr2        | Chromosome of anchor 2              |\n| start2      | Start position of anchor 2          |\n| end2        | End position of anchor 2            |\n| iPET\\_count | Number of supporting iPETs          |\n| expected    | Expected count (distance-corrected) |\n| distance    | Genomic distance between anchors    |\n| p\\_value    | Raw p-value                         |\n| FDR         | Benjamini-Hochberg adjusted p-value |\n\n### Peaks File Format (narrowPeak)\n\n| Column      | Description                       |\n| ----------- | --------------------------------- |\n| chrom       | Chromosome                        |\n| start       | Peak start                        |\n| end         | Peak end                          |\n| name        | Peak name                         |\n| score       | Score                             |\n| strand      | Strand (.)                        |\n| signalValue | Signal value                      |\n| pValue      | -log10(p-value)                   |\n| qValue      | -log10(q-value)                   |\n| peak        | Summit position relative to start |\n\n## HiChIP vs ChIA-PET\n\n| Feature            | HiChIP             | ChIA-PET          |\n| ------------------ | ------------------ | ----------------- |\n| Linker sequences   | **No**             | Yes               |\n| Restriction enzyme | Yes (MboI/DpnII)   | No                |\n| Input requirement  | Low (1M cells)     | High (100M cells) |\n| Purification step  | Fragment-based     | Merge-based       |\n| Statistical model  | Distance-corrected | Standard Poisson  |\n\n## Quality Metrics\n\n**Good HiChIP Data:**\n\n* Mapping rate: >70%\n* Cis ratio: >60%\n* Valid PET ratio: >50%\n* iPET percentage: >40%\n* Peaks called: Depends on protein\n\n**Warning Signs:**\n\n* Low cis ratio (\\<40%): May indicate ligation issues\n* High same-fragment rate (>50%): Incomplete digestion\n* Few peaks: Low enrichment or wrong antibody\n\n## Tips\n\n1. **Restriction Sites**: Always use the correct enzyme for your protocol\n2. **BWA-MEM**: Recommended for HiChIP (`--use-bwa-mem`)\n3. **Distance Correction**: HiChIP uses distance-corrected statistics automatically\n4. **Peak Validation**: Compare peaks with ChIP-seq if available\n5. **Sequencing Depth**: Aim for >100M read pairs for comprehensive analysis\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### High same-fragment rate\n\n* Check restriction enzyme digestion efficiency\n* Verify restriction sites file matches your enzyme\n* Consider re-digestion or protocol optimization\n\n### No peaks called\n\n* Verify antibody specificity\n* Check enrichment with ChIP-seq\n* May need more sequencing depth\n\n### Few significant loops\n\n* Increase sequencing depth\n* Lower FDR threshold for exploration\n* Check if peaks are present (loops anchor at peaks)\n\n### Memory issues\n\n* Reduce threads\n* Process chromosomes separately\n* Use `--keep-intermediates` to debug step-by-step\n";
